<node TEXT="plants.usda.gov &gt; Java &gt; ClassificationServlet ? ..." ID="ID_143311156" CREATED="1395475762938" MODIFIED="1395475762938" LINK="http://plants.usda.gov/java/ClassificationServlet?source=display&amp;classid=AMARA"/>
<node TEXT="&#x9; Magnoliophyta: Magnoliopsida: Caryophyllidae: Caryophyllales: Amaranthaceae: Amaranthus  " ID="ID_1148900320" CREATED="1395475775276" MODIFIED="1395475777831"/>
<node TEXT="Amaranth is gluten free and its seeds contain about 30 percent more protein than rice, sorghum, and rye, according to a USDA Forest Service report. It is also relatively high in calcium, iron, potassium, magnesium, and fiber, according to Puente.&#xa;&#xa;&#x201c;Amaranth&#x2019;s amino acid profile is as close to perfect as you can get for a protein source,&#x201d; Noll said. The plant contains eight essential amino acids and is particularly high in the amino acid lysine, which is largely lacking in corn and wheat, he explained.&#xa;&#xa;&#x201c;So if you make a tortilla with amaranth and corn, you give people a low-cost, culturally acceptable, healthy basic foodstuff,&#x201d; he said.&#xa;&#xa;Florisa Barquera, a doctor and nutritional expert at the Universidad An&#xe1;huac, Mexico City, and a member of the Mexican Academy for Obesity, told National Geographic that amaranth has been recommended by the World Health Organization as a well-balanced food and recommended by NASA for consumption in space missions. The variety of amaranth consumed in Mexico is 16 to 18 percent protein, she said, compared with 14 percent protein in wheat and 9 to 10 percent protein in corn.&#xa;&#xa;Some studies have shown that amaranth also contains beneficial omega-3s and may help reduce blood pressure, said Barquera, who writes and speaks frequently about nutrition in Mexico but is not affiliated with Puente." ID="ID_1211297662" CREATED="1382021086151" MODIFIED="1382021095486"/>
<node TEXT="permaculturefreepress.com &gt;  ? ..." ID="ID_797087441" CREATED="1382021043850" MODIFIED="1382021043850" LINK="http://permaculturefreepress.com/?p=373"/>
<node TEXT="Dark Red Vegetable Amaranth A striking ornamental that grows 4-7 feet in height, this amaranth can be used as a cutting flower, as well as a culinary green. Its leaves are best harvested when young for salad mixes or to cook like spinach. &#x201c;It&apos;s great in curry,&quot; Grant says. &quot;It will stain whatever food it&#x2019;s cooked with, but that can add to the fun,&#x201d; Grant says. Amaranth requires little care in the garden other than to watch for vigorous self-seeding." ID="ID_497265889" CREATED="1423377616057" MODIFIED="1423377619610"/>
