<node TEXT="Prinsepia is a genus of trees in the Rosaceae. It bears fruit which looks like a cherry. The various species grow largely in India, China, Bangladesh, and Taiwan,[2] though P. sinensis is hardy in zone 4, to about -32*C.[3]" ID="ID_1332074402" CREATED="1432398424392" MODIFIED="1432398426485"/>
<node TEXT="Prinsepia are drought tolerant&#xa;They have few pests or diseases&#xa;They should be planted in a sunny location&#xa;Plants are not particular to soil type long as they are well drained" ID="ID_686563780" CREATED="1432398469589" MODIFIED="1432398470847"/>
<node TEXT="Prinsepia is a genus of 4 species in the Rosaceae, native to Asia. They are deciduous shrubs 8-10 feet in height, with alternate leaves with a thorn at the base of the leaf petiole. They produce a tart, orange to purple, cherry-sized fruit that is high in Vitamin C. Plants should probably be grown in groups to aid in pollination. The plants are hardy and appear to able to withstand considerable drought." ID="ID_843381388" CREATED="1432398477585" MODIFIED="1432398489370"/>
</node>
