<node TEXT="Trees" ID="ID_1347492773" CREATED="1372491312795" MODIFIED="1429466624162">
<font NAME="SansSerif" SIZE="18" BOLD="true"/>
<node TEXT="If you can obtain some Willo twigs (Salix species), chop them up into short pieces 2-3&quot; long, and put them into a gallon jar until you can&apos;t get any more in (... well, maybe leave a little room so you can get them out later... don&apos;t pack them that tight...): fill the jar with really hot water to cover the twigs, and let it sit for at least 24 hours. If you use cold water, let the jars sit (in the sunlight) for about 2 weeks. The water pulls a natural growth hormone from the willow, and if you use this to water other plants, their root growth will be stimulated. This stuff even triggers hard-to-root plants like yellow birch and some cherries to put out roots, iirc. This ~should~ increase the success rate when using the method shown in this video." ID="ID_1639478901" CREATED="1372491337091" MODIFIED="1372491341233"/>
<node TEXT="Air Layering" ID="ID_874497067" CREATED="1376544900797" MODIFIED="1429466624165">
<font NAME="SansSerif" SIZE="10" BOLD="true"/>
<node TEXT="Nadine Zdanovich I have heard that you can take some sphagnum moss, scrape part of the bark of a new growth branch, and wrap the sphagnum moss around the scraped part, and then wrap a bit of dense fabric around the sphagnum moss and leave over the spring in to early summer. Then cut below the wrapped area. If the branch has made roots, you can plant it. Sometimes folks cut branch tips and put them in moist sand in a tin so they make roots. Otherwise you make a &apos;graft&apos; take a tip about 6 inches long of a branch and find some scion root-stock, stick the branch tip in cuts made in the root-stock and secure with wax and wrap with string or cord. Definitely google &apos;grafting fruit trees&apos;. If you plant seeds from the fruit, it may not produce the same kind of variety of fruit.&#xa;4 hours ago via mobile &#xb7; Like &#xb7; 1&#xa;&#xa;Jaran Marcel I am also growing seeds as I am really good with convincing the seeds to sprout and grow. If the seeds grow it will really just be so that she can have the child of her father&apos;s tree but I also want to try grafting/cuttings in order to get a true to type clone.&#xa;3 hours ago &#xb7; Like&#xa;&#xa;Nadine Zdanovich Sometimes you get a new &apos;old&apos; variety from the seeds or a completely new one. Both methods should yield some interesting results. Please keep me posted, Jaran!&#xa;3 hours ago via mobile &#xb7; Like&#xa;&#xa;Jaran Marcel Will do! I will probably go see if I can start air layering a branch tomorrow. The biggest problem is that I am going to college and my mother would be in charge of making sure it was cared for until I got back and she is terrible at that! (she killed all of my baby apple trees my first semester away)&#xa;3 hours ago &#xb7; Like&#xa;&#xa;Nadine Zdanovich The good thing about air layering is you set it up and just leave it. It should be ok!&#xa;3 hours ago via mobile &#xb7; Like&#xa;&#xa;Nadine Zdanovich P.S. my construction landscaping guy ran over my Northern Spy sapling, but it lived!&#xa;3 hours ago via mobile &#xb7; Like&#xa;&#xa;Patti Masencup Gibson When I air layer I soak moss in honey and water. I wrap Seran wrap then aluminum foil. Then you can open foil to check to see if you see any roots and close back up if not. I use I vegetable peeler to peel off the outer layer of bark." ID="ID_1887068411" CREATED="1376544908669" MODIFIED="1376544921262"/>
</node>
